# React ID Usage

Use hardcoded IDs only when the element is guaranteed to appear once on a page and the ID must be stable (e.g., single-page form label/field pairs, anchor targets). Prefer `useId()` for reusable components or when multiple instances can render on the same screen.

## Prefer hardcoded IDs when

- The component is used once per page and the ID is a known, stable value.
- The ID must be human-readable or referenced externally (e.g., anchor links).

## Prefer `useId()` when

- The component is reusable and can appear multiple times.
- The component is rendered in lists or repeated sections.
- You need SSR-safe, unique IDs to avoid hydration mismatches.

## Component pattern

Accept an optional `id` prop; fallback to `useId()` when not provided.

```tsx
import { useId } from "react";

type Props = { id?: string };

export function RepoUrlField({ id }: Props) {
  const inputId = id ?? useId();
  return (
    <>
      <Label htmlFor={inputId}>Pull request URL</Label>
      <Input id={inputId} name="prUrl" required />
    </>
  );
}
```

Avoid using IDs for testing selectors; use `data-testid` instead.
